tly refigured global cinema’s form and content. The coincidence of digitalization and globalization has produced what this book helps to define and describe as a flourishing border cinema whose aesthetics reflect, construct, intervene in, denature, and reconfigure geopolitical borders. This collection demonstrates how border cinema resists contemporary border fortification processes, showing how cinematic media have functioned technologically and aesthetically to engender contemporary shifts in national and individual identities while proposing alternative conceptions of these identities to those promulgated by the often restrictive current political rhetoric and ideologies that represent a backlash to globalization.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aBoundaries in motion pictures. 0aDigital cinematography. 0aIdentity (Psychology) in motion pictures. 0aMotion picturesxAesthetics. 7aPERFORMING ARTS / General.2bisacsh  amedia, digital media, borders, global, globalization, digital, cinema, geopolitical, regional border, global cinema.1 aAldama, Frederick Luis, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAldama, Frederick Luis.1 aCapino, José B., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCapino, José.1 aFregoso, Rosa-Linda, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFregoso, Rosa-Linda.1 aGertz, Nurith, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGertz, Nurith.1 aHanna, Monica, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHanna, Monica, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aHassapopoulou, Marina, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHassapopoulou, Marina.1 aLahr-Vivaz, Elena, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/re